original_poem:
amor é um fogo que arde sem se ver,
é ferida que doi, e não se sente;
é um contentamento descontente,
é dor que desatina sem doer.
é um não querer mais que bem querer;
é um andar solitário entre a gente;
é nunca contentar-se de contente;
é um cuidar que ganha em se perder.
é querer estar preso por vontade;
é servir a quem vence, o vencedor;
é ter com quem nos mata, lealdade.
mas como causar pode seu favor
nos corações humanos amizade,
se tão contrário a si é o mesmo amor?

translated_by_TA:
Love is a fire that burns unseen,
a wound that hurts, yet cannot be felt;
it's a discontented contentment,
a pain that maddens without pain.
It's a not wanting more than wanting;
it's a solitary walk among the crowd;
it's never being satisfied when content;
it's caring that gains by losing oneself.
It's wanting to be imprisoned by choice;
it's serving the victor, the conqueror;
it's loyalty to the one who kills us.
But how can it win favor
and sow friendship in human hearts,
when love itself is so contrary to itself?

oh! how my weary pilgrimage extends, year by year,
the tired journey of my life, it seems to go on forever!
how it shortens, and how it nears the end
this brief and futile human discourse of mine!
time is spent and damage grows;
a remedy I had is lost;
if by experience one can guess,
any great hope is a great delusion.
I chase after a good that cannot be reached;
in the middle of the road it fails me,
a thousand times I fall, and lose my trust.
when it flees, I delay; and, in my delay,
if I lift my eyes to see if it still appears,
it disappears from sight and hope.
